  "text": "Because calculating edge betweenness is time-consuming, Radicchi et al. defined a new metric, called link clustering coefficient, to replace it [CITATION_1] . The assumption behind their method is that inter-community links are unlikely to belong to a short loop, such as triangles and squares; otherwise, links in the same loop would likely be across communities, and thus such links would inevitably increase the density of inter-community links. Using this heuristic rule, they define the link clustering coefficient as the number of triangles or squares in which a link is involved. In each iterative step, links with the minimum link clustering coefficient will be cut off. The average time complexity for computing the link clustering coefficient of all links is O(m 3 /n 2 ), lower than that for computing edge betweenness, which is O(mn). Thus, their method is on average faster than GN with the time complexity of O(m 4 /n 2 ).",
